            <fr:title text="Brownian motion">Brownian motion</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors />
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>A Standard Brownian Motion (often denoted as <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B_t]]></fr:tex> or <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[W_t]]></fr:tex>) is a <fr:link type="local" href="SP-0004.xml" addr="SP-0004" title="Stochastic Process">stochastic process</fr:link> satisfying the following four properties:</fr:p>
            <fr:ol><fr:li><fr:strong>Starting Point</fr:strong>: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B_0 = 0]]></fr:tex> (<fr:link type="local" href="SP-0002.xml" addr="SP-0002" title="Almost surely">almost surely</fr:link>). This means the process starts at the origin.</fr:li>

  <fr:li><fr:strong>Independent Increments</fr:strong>: For any non-overlapping time intervals, the increments of the process are independent. That is, for any <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[0 \leq  s_1 \leq  t_1 \leq  s_2 \leq  t_2]]></fr:tex>, the increment <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B_{t_1} - B_{s1}]]></fr:tex> is independent of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B_{t_2} - B_{s2}]]></fr:tex>. More generally, all increments are independent</fr:li>

  <fr:li><fr:strong>Stationary and Normally Distributed Increments</fr:strong> For all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[ 0\leq  s \leq  t ]]></fr:tex>, we have that 
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       B_t - B_s \sim  \mathcal {N} (0, t-s)     ]]></fr:tex></fr:li>

  <fr:li><fr:strong>Continuity of Paths</fr:strong>: The sample paths (or realizations) of the Brownian motion are continuous functions of time. This means there are <fr:em>no sudden jumps</fr:em> in the particle's position.</fr:li></fr:ol>
          </fr:mainmatter>
